                  <handDesc>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Rather fine but slightly uneven</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red.</seg>
                        <date>19th century</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>Some of the abbreviations used throughout the text:</item>
                           <item>ማ፡/ማኅ፡/ማኅሌ፡ for ማኅሌት፡</item>
                           <item>ምል፡/ምልጣ፡ for ምልጣን፡</item>
                           <item>ም፡ for ምስባክ፡</item>
                           <item>መዝ፡/መዝሙ፡ for መዝሙር፡</item>
                           <item>እስ፡ for እስመ፡</item>
                           <item>እግዚ፡/እግዚአ፡ ነግ፡ for እግዚአብሔር፡ ነግሠ፡</item>
                           <item>ዋዜ፡ for ዋዜማ፡</item>
                           <item>ዘይእ፡ for ዘይእዜ፡</item>
                           <item>ይት፡/ይትባ፡ for ይትባረክ፡</item>
                           <item>ቅንዋ፡ for ቅንዋት፡</item>
                           <item>ቃለ፡ ዓ፡ for ቃለ፡ ዓዋዲ፡</item>
                           <item>ብፁ፡ for ብፁዕ፡</item>
                           <item>አምላክ፡ for አምላኪየ፡</item>
                           <item>አራራ፡ for አራራይ፡</item>
                           <item>ዕ፡/ዕዝ፡ for ዕዝል፡</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>Repeated versicles are often written in an abbreviated form,
                                 e.g., ይ፤ሆ፤በ stands</abbr> for <expan>ይብሉ፡ ሆሳዕና፡ በአርያም </expan>
                                 (<locus target="#25ra">25ra</locus> l.9).</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">1st and 3rd line on the incipit page of the text;
                           names of sections followed by feast names (e.g., wāzemā za-masqal, wāzemā
                           za-ʾarbaʿǝtu ʾǝnsǝsa); names of antiphons and their abbreviations (e.g.,
                           māḥlet, mazmur, śalast, salām, ba-5-tu, ʾabun, ʾaryām, ʾǝsma la-ʿālam,
                           za-ʾamlākiya, za-yǝʾǝze, yǝtbārak); names of other chants and their
                           abbreviations (e.g., mǝlṭān, mǝsbak, ʿǝzl); musical notation:
                           intratextual signs (e.g., sǝräyu, qadāmi, yǝgäbru, qāla ʿawadi, ʾaklilä,
                           täsäfḥa) and elements of marginal signs; elements of the Table of
                           halleluiatic chants; names of the categories of melody and their
                           abbreviations (ʿǝzl, gǝʿǝz, ʾararay); red and black dot chains separating
                           sections and groups of antiphons belonging to different liturgical hours
                           within the same day; elements of the punctuation signs; Ethiopic numerals
                           or their elements. 
 
 Lack of rubrication on fols.
                           46va-49vb.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>

                     <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d1">
                        <locus target="#14vb">14vb</locus>: A frame composed of alternating black
                        and red dots.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d2">
                        <locus target="#20vb">20vb</locus>: A short horizontal band with two
                        parallel white lines and two chains of black and red triangles.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <list>
                        <item xml:id="e1">- Title of the work, መዝሙር, is written on the front cover. - Lack of musical notation on fols. 47rb-49vb. - Tämälläs signs indicating the place where the omissions, written in the margins, belong: fols. 9ra l.6, 35va l.8. - Omitted passages are written in the upper margin, in the main hand: fols. 16vb, 18va.</item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
